{"section": "3.12.4: Strong induction.", "qid": 2, "instructions": "<div class=\"activity-instructions\">\n <p>\n  Consider again the problem of purchasing cans of juice. Suppose now that juice is sold in 2-packs\nor 5-packs. Let Q(n) be the statement that it is possible to buy n cans of juice by combining 2-packs and\n5-packs. This problem discusses using strong induction to prove that for any n \u2265 4,\nQ(n) is true.\n </p>\n</div>\n", "question": "<div class=\"question\">\n <div class=\"setup flex-row\">\n  <div class=\"label\">\n   3)\n  </div>\n  <div class=\"text\">\n   In the base case, for which values of n should Q(n) be proven directly?\n  </div>\n </div>\n <fieldset>\n  <div class=\"zb-radio-button orange orange ember-view\" id=\"ember180\" style=\"\">\n   <input aria-label=\"n = 3, n = 4, and \nn = 5.\" name=\"43\" type=\"radio\" value=\"&lt;(unknown):ember179&gt;\"/>\n   <label aria-hidden=\"true\" style=\"\">\n    n = 3, n = 4, and\n    <span style=\"white-space: nowrap;\">\n     n = 5.\n    </span>\n   </label>\n  </div>\n  <div class=\"zb-radio-button orange orange ember-view\" id=\"ember182\" style=\"\">\n   <input aria-label=\"n = 4 and n = 5.\" name=\"43\" type=\"radio\" value=\"&lt;(unknown):ember181&gt;\"/>\n   <label aria-hidden=\"true\" style=\"\">\n    n = 4 and n = 5.\n   </label>\n  </div>\n  <div class=\"zb-radio-button orange orange ember-view\" id=\"ember184\">\n   <input aria-label=\"n = 4, n = 5, and \nn = 6.\" name=\"43\" type=\"radio\" value=\"&lt;(unknown):ember183&gt;\"/>\n   <label aria-hidden=\"true\">\n    n = 4, n = 5, and\n    <span style=\"white-space: nowrap;\">\n     n = 6.\n    </span>\n   </label>\n  </div>\n </fieldset>\n</div>\n", "choices": ["<div class=\"zb-radio-button orange orange ember-view\" id=\"ember180\">\n <input aria-label=\"n = 3, n = 4, and \nn = 5.\" name=\"43\" type=\"radio\" value=\"&lt;(unknown):ember179&gt;\"/>\n <label aria-hidden=\"true\">\n  n = 3, n = 4, and\n  <span style=\"white-space: nowrap;\">\n   n = 5.\n  </span>\n </label>\n</div>\n", "<div class=\"zb-radio-button orange orange ember-view\" id=\"ember182\">\n <input aria-label=\"n = 4 and n = 5.\" name=\"43\" type=\"radio\" value=\"&lt;(unknown):ember181&gt;\"/>\n <label aria-hidden=\"true\">\n  n = 4 and n = 5.\n </label>\n</div>\n", "<div class=\"zb-radio-button orange orange ember-view\" id=\"ember184\">\n <input aria-label=\"n = 4, n = 5, and \nn = 6.\" name=\"43\" type=\"radio\" value=\"&lt;(unknown):ember183&gt;\"/>\n <label aria-hidden=\"true\">\n  n = 4, n = 5, and\n  <span style=\"white-space: nowrap;\">\n   n = 6.\n  </span>\n </label>\n</div>\n"], "answer": "n = 4 and n = 5.", "explanation": "<div aria-atomic=\"true\" class=\"explanation has-explanation correct\" role=\"alert\">\n <p class=\"message\">\n  Correct\n </p>\n The inductive step uses Q(k - 1) to prove\n <span style=\"white-space: nowrap;\">\n  Q(k + 1).\n </span>\n <span style=\"white-space: nowrap;\">\n  k - 1\n </span>\n is two less than\n <span style=\"white-space: nowrap;\">\n  k + 1.\n </span>\n Therefore\ntwo consecutive values are required for the base case, starting at\n <span style=\"white-space: nowrap;\">\n  n = 4.\n </span>\n</div>\n"}